<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-126-113 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 041 311</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Executive  Summer 1991 v4 n3 p17(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Organizational implications of expert systems.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Raho, Louis E.; Drehmer, David; Belohav, James.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Expert systems, although presently a small portion of informationsystems technology, are being used for a wide range ofapplications at an increasing rate.andP;  In 1987 there were 50 expertsystems deployed; in 1988 there were 1,400.andP;  The number of expertsystems under development increased from 2,500 to 8,500 in thesame time span, according to Raj Reddy, in an address to theAmerican Association for Artificial Intelligence.andP;  Expert systemsmay be a way to provide increased quality, productivity andinnovation for almost all segments of organizational activity.andP;  Arandom sample of 1,858 members of the Data Processing ManagementAssociation resulted in the return of 505 usable questionnaires.andO;Top management accounted for 46.7 percent of the respondents, andoperations accounted for 53.3 percent of the respondents.andP;  Thegreatest priority for the respondents was internal processes,rather than those that concerned external focus.andP;  Detailed surveyresults are given.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     SurveyExpert SystemsInformation Resources ManagementAnalysisOrganizational BehaviorData Processing Management Association.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Perceptions of expert system value for various functional areas.andO;(chart)Organizational impacts of expert systems. (chart)Reasons for adopting expert system. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>